## Problem
`parseMeasurementSpecResponse()` in `measurement-spec.ts` does minimal validation — checks entities/events are arrays, entity_id references exist, confidence is a number. But it doesn't validate:
- Entity ID format: `/^[a-z][a-z0-9_]*$/` (per system prompt line 42)
- Event name format: `/^[a-z][a-z0-9]*_[a-z][a-z0-9_]*$/` (per system prompt line 58)
- Perspective enum: must be `customer | product | interaction`
- Category enum: must be `activation | value | retention | expansion`
- Exactly one entity has `isHeartbeat: true`

LLM may return malformed data that is silently accepted and persisted.

## Implementation Plan

### Step 1: Define validation constants (measurement-spec.ts, before line 300)

Add regex constants and valid enum sets just above `parseMeasurementSpecResponse()`:

```typescript
// --- Validation Constants ---
const ENTITY_ID_RE = /^[a-z][a-z0-9_]*$/;
const EVENT_NAME_RE = /^[a-z][a-z0-9]*_[a-z][a-z0-9_]*$/;
const VALID_PERSPECTIVES = new Set(["customer", "product", "interaction"]);
const VALID_CATEGORIES = new Set(["activation", "value", "retention", "expansion"]);
```

These mirror the exact rules stated in `MEASUREMENT_SPEC_SYSTEM_PROMPT` (lines 42, 58, 63-66, 69-73).

### Step 2: Add entity ID format validation (after line 331, inside the entity loop)

After `entityIds.add(entity.id);` on line 331, add:

```typescript
if (!ENTITY_ID_RE.test(entity.id)) {
  throw new Error(
    `Entity '${entity.id}': id must match /^[a-z][a-z0-9_]*$/ (lowercase, starts with letter, only letters/digits/underscores)`
  );
}
```

### Step 3: Add heartbeat uniqueness validation (after the entity loop, line 332)

After the existing entity `for` loop closes, add:

```typescript
const heartbeatEntities = (parsed.entities as Array<Record<string, unknown>>)
  .filter((e) => e.isHeartbeat === true);
if (heartbeatEntities.length === 0) {
  throw new Error("Exactly one entity must have isHeartbeat: true, but none found");
}
if (heartbeatEntities.length > 1) {
  const ids = heartbeatEntities.map((e) => e.id).join(", ");
  throw new Error(
    `Exactly one entity must have isHeartbeat: true, but found ${heartbeatEntities.length}: ${ids}`
  );
}
```

### Step 4: Add event name format, perspective, and category validation (inside the event loop, after line 341)

After the existing `entity_id` reference check on line 340-341, add:

```typescript
if (!EVENT_NAME_RE.test(event.name)) {
  throw new Error(
    `Event '${event.name}': name must match /^[a-z][a-z0-9]*_[a-z][a-z0-9_]*$/ (entity_action format)`
  );
}

const perspective = event.perspective as string;
if (!VALID_PERSPECTIVES.has(perspective)) {
  throw new Error(
    `Event '${event.name}': perspective must be one of [customer, product, interaction], got '${perspective}'`
  );
}

const category = event.category as string;
if (!VALID_CATEGORIES.has(category)) {
  throw new Error(
    `Event '${event.name}': category must be one of [activation, value, retention, expansion], got '${category}'`
  );
}
```

### Step 5: Decision — strict (throw), not lenient

**Use strict validation (throw).** Rationale:
- The system prompt already tells the LLM exactly what formats to use
- Silently accepting bad data is worse than failing fast — downstream consumers (CLI export, storage) will persist malformed specs
- The other parsers in the same directory (`parseActivationMapResponse`) also throw on validation failures
- If the LLM consistently fails a check, we should fix the prompt — not silently accept bad data
- The `MeasurementSpec` type already has an optional `warnings?: string[]` field, but it's better used for soft quality signals (like perspective balance being off), not for format violations

### Files to Modify

1. **`packages/mcp-server/src/analysis/outputs/measurement-spec.ts`** (lines 298-342)
   - Add 4 constants before the function
   - Add entity ID format check inside entity loop
   - Add heartbeat uniqueness check after entity loop
   - Add event name, perspective, category checks inside event loop

2. **`packages/mcp-server/src/analysis/__tests__/outputs/measurement-spec.test.ts`**
   - Add new test cases (see Test Plan below)

## Test Plan

Add a new `describe` block: `"parseMeasurementSpecResponse — format validation"` with these test cases:

### Entity ID format tests
1. **"rejects entity ID starting with digit"** — `{ id: "1issue", ... }` → throws with `id must match`
2. **"rejects entity ID with uppercase"** — `{ id: "Issue", ... }` → throws with `id must match`
3. **"rejects entity ID with hyphens"** — `{ id: "my-entity", ... }` → throws with `id must match`
4. **"accepts valid entity ID with underscores"** — `{ id: "project_board", ... }` → no throw

### Heartbeat uniqueness tests
5. **"rejects zero heartbeat entities"** — all entities have `isHeartbeat: false` → throws `none found`
6. **"rejects multiple heartbeat entities"** — two entities with `isHeartbeat: true` → throws `found 2`
7. **"accepts exactly one heartbeat entity"** — one entity has `isHeartbeat: true` → no throw (covered by existing happy-path test)

### Event name format tests
8. **"rejects event name without underscore"** — `{ name: "issuecreated", ... }` → throws `name must match`
9. **"rejects event name starting with uppercase"** — `{ name: "Issue_created", ... }` → throws `name must match`
10. **"rejects event name starting with underscore"** — `{ name: "_issue_created", ... }` → throws `name must match`
11. **"accepts valid multi-segment event name"** — `{ name: "board_column_moved", ... }` → no throw

### Perspective enum tests
12. **"rejects invalid perspective"** — `{ perspective: "user", ... }` → throws `perspective must be one of`
13. **"rejects missing perspective"** — `{ perspective: undefined, ... }` → throws `perspective must be one of`

### Category enum tests
14. **"rejects invalid category"** — `{ category: "engagement", ... }` → throws `category must be one of`
15. **"rejects missing category"** — `{ category: undefined, ... }` → throws `category must be one of`

### Edge cases
16. **"rejects event name with only prefix (no action)"** — `{ name: "issue_", ... }` → throws (trailing underscore doesn't match regex since `_[a-z]` requires a letter after underscore)
17. **"accepts event name with digits in entity prefix"** — `{ name: "v2board_created", ... }` → no throw (matches `[a-z][a-z0-9]*`)

### Helper: test factory

Create a helper function `makeValidSpec(overrides)` that returns a valid JSON string, to reduce boilerplate. The helper generates a spec with one entity (`id: "issue"`, `isHeartbeat: true`) and one event (`name: "issue_created"`, `perspective: "customer"`, `category: "activation"`). Individual tests override just the field being tested.

```typescript
function makeValidSpecJson(overrides: {
  entities?: Array<Record<string, unknown>>;
  events?: Array<Record<string, unknown>>;
} = {}): string {
  const defaultEntity = {
    id: "issue", name: "Issue", description: "Work item",
    isHeartbeat: true,
    properties: [{ name: "issue_id", type: "string", description: "ID", isRequired: true }],
  };
  const defaultEvent = {
    name: "issue_created", entity_id: "issue", description: "Created",
    perspective: "customer",
    properties: [
      { name: "title", type: "string", description: "T", required: true },
      { name: "p", type: "string", description: "P", required: false },
    ],
    trigger_condition: "When created",
    maps_to: { type: "value_moment", moment_id: "vm-1" },
    category: "activation",
  };
  return JSON.stringify({
    entities: overrides.entities ?? [defaultEntity],
    events: overrides.events ?? [defaultEvent],
    userStateModel: [
      { name: "new", definition: "D", criteria: [] },
    ],
    confidence: 0.7,
  });
}
```

